{{Coord|58|21|40.16|N|25|36|25.32|E|type:landmark|display=title}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Viljandi linnastaadion | nickname = | image = Viljandi Linnastaadion-Bench.JPG | image_size = 250px | location = [[Viljandi]], [[Estonia]] | broke_ground = 1928 | opened = | closed = | demolished = | renovated = 1980, 2009 | owner = [[Viljandi|City of Viljandi]]<ref name="eok">[http://www.eok.ee/spordirajatised?view=spordiklubid&type=1&id=402&mk=2&sport_filt=&vars=3 EOK - Spordirajatised — VILJANDI LINNASTAADION] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717135528/http://www.eok.ee/spordirajatised?view=spordiklubid&type=1&id=402&mk=2&sport_filt=&vars=3 |date=July 17, 2011 }}</ref> | operator = MA Viljandi Spordikeskus | dimensions = 104 × 69 m<ref name="eok" /> | surface = Grass | construction_cost = 1,510,000 € (2009) | architect = | former_names = | tenants = <center>[[FC Viljandi (2011)|FC Viljandi]] ([[Meistriliiga]]) | seating_capacity = 1,006<ref name="eok" /> }}
'''Viljandi linnastaadion''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Viljandi]], [[Estonia]]. It is used mostly for [[football (soccer)|football]] matches and hosts the matches of [[FC Viljandi (2011)|FC Viljandi]]. The stadium has 1,006 seats of which 400 are under the roof.
==History== The building of the stadium started in 1928, when the mayor of Viljandi was [[August Maramaa]]. Because of the downturn in economy, the building was not completed before [[World War II]].
Previous renovation before 2009 was done in the beginning of the 1980s. After that reconstruction, the stadium could hold up to 2,506 people.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}
